# 4. いざ、アロマキャンドル作り！

Nene: Th-Thank you for having us over.
Kanade: Please, come in. It's not very spacious, but feel free to move the furniture around and sit wherever you like.
Nene: O-Okay. Thank you very much.
Kanade: I'll pour us some tea. Let's see... Where did I put the tea bags we bought the other day...?
Honami: Oh, Ms. Yoisaki, that's okay. I don't mind doing it...
Kanade: No, you're not here to work today, so please make yourself at home.
Honami: But...
Kanade: Oh... I need to boil some water first... I'll fill the kettle with some water and... Hnng... I-It's so heavy...
Honami: I-Is everything okay, Ms. Yoisaki? Are you sure you don't want me to help?
Kanade: S-Sorry... Then, if you don't mind...
Ichika: Ahh... Thank you for the tea, Honami, Kanade.
Nene: Oh, um... It was delicious. Thank you for making that for us.
Kanade: Thank goodness... I'm glad it actually turned out well... I couldn't have done it without your help, Ms. Mochizuki.
Kanade: Although, I was really hoping to make some for you all by myself... Thank you, and I'm sorry.
Honami: No, you don't need to thank me. If anything, I really appreciate the gesture.
Honami: Alright, now that we've had a chance to relax a little, shall we start making our scented candles...?
Nene: O-Okay. Again, thank you for doing this.
Honami: Not to worry. Scented candles are very easy to make. All we have to do is melt down some store-bought candles, mix in the oils we bought earlier and reharden them.
Ichika: Just melt and reharden them...?
Nene: It does seem a lot easier when you put it that way...
Honami: Hehe. I felt the same way when I first learned how to do this. Regardless, let's just take it one step at a time.
Honami: First, you'll each need to choose some crayons to give your candles color.
Kanade: Crayons will give them their color...?
Honami: Yes, you shave off bits of crayons and mix them into the wax. You won't believe how beautifully this works.
Honami: I recommend choosing colors that go with the fragrances you chose or even using multiple to create several layers of colors.
Kanade: Several layers...? You can do that...?
Honami: Yes. Of course, you don't have to choose any colors at all... However, since we're doing this, I thought it'd be nice if we all did.
Kanade: Yes, I agree. I'd like to give it a try...
Honami: Once you've chosen a color, we'll use a double boiler to melt down the wax. I'll start us off...
Honami: First, we'll need three large pots and bowls... You heat the bowls with boiling water and use them to melt the wax.
Nene: It seems kinda strange to melt candles for their wax...
Ichika: Yeah... But this process is sort of similar to how you make your own chocolates.
Nene: Oh, you're right.
Kanade: The wax is starting to melt... Wait, what's this...? It looks like a piece of string...
Honami: Ah, that's the wick. We'll save that as we'll be using it later...
Honami: Now we just need to wait a little longer for the candles to melt.
Honami: Okay, they seem ready. Next, we'll start mixing in the crayons you've all chosen. Why don't we do this part together?
Ichika: O-Okay... Wait... How much do we need to put in...?
Honami: Hmm... Not a lot. If you put in too much, it may cause the wick to not light because it isn't able to absorb the wax properly.
Kanade: What...?
Honami: No, don't worry! I'll be right here to make sure you don't put in too much.
Kanade: O-Okay. That's a relief... I think...
Ichika: (So... Carefully put some crayon shavings in... Little by little...)
Ichika: H-Honami, is this enough...?
Honami: Oh, you don't have to be so careful... You can put a little more in.
Ichika: R-Really...? Then... H-How's this...?!
Honami: Yes, good...! That should be plenty, Ichika. Now, just mix the wax and... Oh, see. It's changing colors already.
Ichika: I-It is... That's incredible. It changed completely...
Kanade: Um... Does mine look okay...?
Honami: Oh, Ms. Yoisaki, Kusanagi, you're both doing a wonderful job...!
Nene: Th-Thank you... That's good to hear.
Honami: Okay, next... We need our wax to cool off a bit. Our oil will evaporate and lose its scent if we put it in when it's still hot.
Ichika: Really...? So, we're taking a short break?
Honami: Yes, but it shouldn't take too long. In the meantime, why don't we choose which fragrances we're going to mix in?
Honami: Okay... They seem to be at about the right temperature...
Honami: So, everyone, please take your bowls and put in roughly ten drops of your scented oil.
Nene: O-Okay... Ten drops...
Kanade: I hope I don't lose count... Or make it come out all at once...
Ichika: I-I'm sure you'll be fine. It's meant to add a nice scent to your candle, so adding a little more than suggested shouldn't be...
Honami: Oh, if you put in too much oil, the wick will have trouble lighting...
Honami: U-Uh, but... You don't have to be super precise either...!
Honami: We'll reheat our wax again a little and mix it up... Also, everyone, do you have your molds ready?
Ichika: Yeah, here's mine. Um... We place the wick in the middle, right?
Honami: Yes, that's right. The wick will go there and you'll keep it in place using a pair of chopsticks.
Honami: After that, you'll pour in your wax.
Ichika: Okay. I'll give it a try...!
Honami: Then, Ichika, here's your bowl... Be careful not to spill any, okay?
Ichika: O-Okay...
Ichika: (Gently carry my bowl over and... Oh...)
Ichika: (Wow, that's really nice... It's already starting to smell like oranges...)
Ichika: (It's even turned bright orange. This candle might actually turn out really well.)
Ichika: (I hope Saki likes my present to her...)
Ichika: (Okay, now... Carefully pour the wax in...)
Ichika: Okay, I did it...!
Honami: Hehe. Nicely done, Ichika.
Ichika: Thanks! So, what's next...?
Honami: Next...?
Honami: That's it.
Kanade, Nene & Ichika: What?
Honami: All that's left is to wait for the wax to reharden. The final step of the process was to pour it into the molds.
Honami: See? Wasn't it easy?
Nene: Y-Yeah... I was under the impression that there were more steps, but I guess that's it...
Kanade: I didn't think it would be this easy either...
Honami: Hehe. It should only get easier once you've gotten a hang of this process. So this time, why don't you try melting the wax yourselves?
Honami: And please feel free to ask for help if you get stuck. I'll be there with you every step of the way.
